After half an hour, the charred tuber is taken and swallowed up with eager, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also carries out her daily work, e.g. B. Washing clothes with murky water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless space serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she was not assigned fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most village men are unemployed, and many drink heavy, and there are the soldiers here.
"Nobody dares to walk around the village after 5 pm," she says.
It is a rare insight into the daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony, which was admitted in 1969 after a controversial referendum in Indonesia, when only 1,026 elders were to vote in front of the occupying forces by a public hand survey.
An existing movement, which moved in favour of independence against Dutch rule, quickly turned against the government of Jakarta, which maintains control over the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea covering the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is barren. The trip includes a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire and then a 5-hour car hire car ride.
