There were also other changes.
"We were not used to wearing this clothes," says Degei, pointing to her lively, hand-woven turban, dark shirt and bright skirt.
"We used to have only leaves on our bodies."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, where 28% of people live below the poverty line and have some of the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia's Goldland.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by the Phoenix Freeport McMoran, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a New Jersey-sized highland province with 153,000 inhabitants.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined gold and copper worth 3.1 billion US dollars.
In addition, Papua has wood resources worth an estimated 78 billion US dollars.
However, these riches are a source of misery for the Papuans, which ensure that Indonesia's powerful military preserves a suffocating presence.
A 2005 investigation in the New York Times reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly 20 million dollars between 1998 and 2004, including up to 150,000 dollars to a single officer.
