NHS (National Health Service) to prescribe controversial HIV drug 10,000 people
Patients will have access to "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September after a fight before the High Court against the financing of the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that pre-intermobility pre-intermail prevention (PrEP) that can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 percent is now being supplied by a health service through a first three-year study for estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year, according to which the NHS had the power to pay for the PrEP despite the claim that local authorities should fund it.
The move announced on Thursday was welcomed by NHS England boss Simon Stevens as an "important new intervention", while the National Aids Trust (NAT) called this a "decisive moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to enable people to register, and more clinics will follow in October before being introduced throughout England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a consequence of HIV preparations that are taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in infection-risked.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that just enough drugs are present in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day or so two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those who are eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics identifies appropriate participants who agree to the study, including men, women, transgenders and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a family doctor can also register for possible participation in their local participating sex clinic.
The program will signed a contract to deliver the medicines this week after an international competitive procurement of 10 million dollars and NHS England.
The study is intended to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on how it is targeted, included and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention should complement and overtake far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in which more than three decades of continued progress in addressing one of humanity's biggest health challenges."
Deborah Gold, NAT's chief executive (National Aids Trust), said: "This is a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted at needy and vulnerable people, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
From September onwards, people with high HIV risk will have access to this NHS-funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and is not subject to a negotiation with a partner, which leads to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement."
Ian Green, Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority now must be that the study is quickly conducted throughout the country and that no one who has a risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that PrEP test medicine has been procured, we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people infected with HIV."
Sharon Hodgson, shadow health minister, said: "The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delay and delay and delayed implementation by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and how it can stop the transmission of this life-changing infection.
This try brings us one step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that this study is conducted throughout the country as quickly as possible to protect people who are HIV-infected and that it will help us get one step closer to ending the prevalence of HIV in society.'
